    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-06-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="253" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d253">
                <head>No. 249.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Steele</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>
                            <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-06-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 8,
                                1886</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your letter of June 5,
                            giving at length your views upon the present “relation of American
                            fisheries with England and her provinces.”</p>
                <p>Your discussion of the situation is comprehensive, and will receive due
                            consideration.</p>
                <p>The chief remedy you propose—the levy of a tariff duty of 1 cent per
                            pound upon fresh and salt fish—is, of course, solely for the
                            consideration of Congress.</p>
                <p>The object and earnest endeavor of the Executive will be to secure
                            American citizens the full enjoyment of all the rights under treaties
                            and law without molestation, and no effort to that end has been or will
                            be lacking on the part of those charged with the administration of the
                            laws.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
